  • ■ Motivation

EPS Performance and Robustness Evolution

<number>

Criteria

Open-Loop Control

Closed-Loop Control

<number>

Road Feel / Vehicle Condition
Perception of mu-change, uneven surfaces, bank angle, over steer, under steer, …

Natural balance of forces reflect road surface and vehicle condition

Requires special detection and control action to reflect changes in the road surface and vehicle condition

Disturbance Rejection

Capability for rejecting disturbances from road, motor, vehicle, etc.

Requires specific algorithms and tuning

Closed-loop control inherently rejects disturbances, depending on disturbance frequency and servo bandwidth

Performance Robustness

Robustness to variations in manufacturing, friction, wear, usage, ...

Dedicated algorithms required to manage performance variation (Friction Learn/Comp Temperature Comp, SRS Comp, Active Pull Comp)

Compensates for variations by design to give consistent performance

Tuning Interface
Relationship between tuning parameters and steering feel

Friction & Damping: compensate effects to get desired friction & damping feel

Assist: Indirect relationship to driver torque.

Effort: open-loop estimation of driver torque

Friction & Damping: directly calibrate desired steering feel performance

Effort: direct relationship to driver torque

Tuning Process
Coupling among the tuning parameters, tuning difficulty and time

Desired feel is achievable but requires a structured tuning process and iterations
(processes are well developed)

High level functions such as effort, return, and damping have less coupling

Tuning Portability

Ease of porting tuning across platforms

Limited portability, but mature industry experience

Tuning calibrations potentially portable, but depends on vehicle response

Some calibrations require vehicle test data

Motor Optimization

PP-124: Cost Optimized Motor Design (IPM/skew/pole shape/WIH)

  • ■ Description 

    • −Develop Cost Optimized Motor 

  • ■Motivation (10) 

    • −Reduce Material cost in Motor 

  • ■Deliverables 

    • −Determine if Larger OD Rotor is a Cost Advantage 

    • −Determine if Higher Grade Magnets vs cost is a feasible option 

    • −Determine which stator / winding  design is optimal for cost 

    • −Determine if shape of magnet has cost impact 

  • ■Timing 

    • −Fiasa & PSA BMPV (2016 - SOP) 

  • ■Team Members/Customers 

    • −Rakib Islam 

    • −Bryan Williams 

    • −Ken Webber 

    • −Steve Collier-Hallman 

    • −John Redwine 

Cost Motor Model and
Cogging Cancellation

<number>

PP-126: Heat Management for Motor

  • ■ Description 

    • −Reduce Motor generated heat from Segment/Needle Stator designs 

  • ■Motivation (9) 

    • −Segment and Needle Wind Motors with plastic Insulators generate more heat than Shed Wound motors 

  • ■Deliverables 

    • −Determine if gap filler can be added prior to winding to get direct heat transfer to stator 

    • −Determine if thermally conductive coatings (Bergquist epoxy coat) on stator instead of plastic insulator reduces motor thermals. 

    • −Determine which stator / winding  design is optimal for thermals 

  • ■Timing 

    • −Fiasa & PSA BMPV (SOP - 2016) 

  • ■Team Members/Customers 

    • −Rakib Islam 

    • −Bryan Williams 

    • −Ken Webber 

    • −Joanne Tersigni 

    • −Julie Kleinau
